1005","before 1013":"vóór 1013","0970":"0970","1058":"1058","1013":"1013","before 1033":"vóór 1033","BEF. 1033":"vóór 1033","1057":"1057","0990":"0990","1033":"1033","about 1032":"circa 1032","about 1033":"circa 1033","Lumphanan, Scotland":"Lumphanan, Aberdeenshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Northumbria, England":"Northumbria, England","Europe":"Europa","Iona, Argyll and Bute, Scotland":"Iona, Argyll and Bute, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Inverness, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness, Inverness-shire, Schotland"},"en":{"1013–1057":"1013–1057","0970–1033":"0970–1033","1005–1057":"1005–1057","1033–1058":"1033–1058","0990–1033":"0990–1033","0990–Female":"0990–Deceased","1005":"1005","before 1013":"before 1013","0970":"0970","1058":"1058","1013":"1013","before 1033":"before 1033","BEF. 1033":"before 1033","1057":"1057","0990":"0990","1033":"1033","about 1032":"about 1032","about 1033":"about 1033","Lumphanan, Scotland":"Lumphanan, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Northumbria, England":"Northumbria, England","Europe":"Europe","Iona, Argyll and Bute, Scotland":"Iona, Argyll and Bute, Scotland, United Kingdom","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Scotland, United Kingdom","Inverness, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness, Inverness-shire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"mi","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 米, which means ‘rice’: (i) from one of the ‘Nine Sogdian Surnames’, also known as ‘nine surnames of Zhaowu’, because their ancestors came from Zhaowu, an ancient city in present-day Gansu province in northwestern China. During the Sui and Tang dynasties (581–987  AD ) there were nine Sogdian states in Central Asia, one of which was called Mi (米) in Chinese (located in present-day Uzbekistan). Between 649 and 655  AD , these states submitted to the Emperor Gaozong of Tang (628–683  AD ). Immigrants from the state of Mi to China acquired the surname 米. (ii) for some families, the surname is borne by descendants of Mi Fu (米芾), an artist in the Northern Song dynasty (960–1127  AD ), who claimed he was a descendant from the royal families of the state of Chu in the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) and changed his original surname 芈 to 米, a different Chinese character with the same pronunciation.","Mandarin form of the surname 宓 (also pronounced as Fu in Mandarin): (i) said to be borne by descendants of Fu Xi (伏羲), a legendary figure prior to the Xia dynasty (2070–1600  BC ). (ii) said to be traced back to Mi Kang Gong (密康公, also written as 宓康公, Duke Kang of Mi, died 922  BC ), ruler of the state of Mi during the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC )."],"variants":[{"name":"Mai","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Thanh, Hoa, Son, Dung, Long, Binh, Minh, Thu, Hue, Huong, Thuy.  Chinese Chi, Hong, Ho, Sang, Han, Hang, Jian, Li, Man, Mei, Sen, Wei.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 麥, meaning ‘wheat’ in Chinese: (i) from Mai Qiu (麥丘), the title of a man in the state of Qi (located mainly in present-day Shandong province) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), who, despite being very old, came to celebrate the birthday of the Duke Huan of Qi (ruler of the state of Qi, died 643  BC ). His descendants inherited 麥, the first part of his title, as their surname. (ii) borne by descendants of Mai Tie Zhang (麥鐵杖), a famous general during the Sui dynasty (581–618  AD ). His descendants were scattered around southern China.","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 買, meaning ‘buy’ in Chinese: (i) borne by descendants of the king Song Weizi, founder of the state of Song. (ii) borne by descendants of the Duke Dao of Xu (ruler of the state of Xu, 546–523  BC ), possibly inheriting his personal name. (iii) from the first element of the personal name Mai Zhu Chu (買朱鉏), style name of an official who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iv) it has also been traced back to other ethnic groups in northern China."]},{"name":"Bi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Weihua, Cheng, Hui, Keping, Kun, Lei, Li Ping, Ming, Qi, Tao, Weizhen, Wenyi.  Vietnamese Chau, Hai, Hao, Hung, Mui, Nguyen, Nhung, Tran, Tuan.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 畢, originally denoting a kind of hand-net used in hunting or meaning ‘to complete’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the placename Bi (畢), the name of a fief (located in present-day Shaanxi province), which was granted to Bi Gong Gao (畢公高, or Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (1152–1056  BC ). (ii) adopted as a surname by the Chu Lian (出連) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 秘 (also pronounced as Bei or Mi in Mandarin in some local regions), meaning ‘secret’ in Chinese: surname traced back to some powerful clans in the Qiang minority ethnic group in ancient western China."]},{"name":"Lua","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Francisco, Jesus, Juan, Dalia, Fernando, Ignacio, Jose Luis, Josefina, Luis, Manuel, Mario.","Galician (<b>Lúa</b>): habitational name from a place called Lúa in Lugo province (Galicia, Spain), from the name of a river, of pre-Roman origin. This surname is apparently no longer found in Galicia (Spain).","Hawaiian: unexplained."]}]},{"name":"Gruoch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Andrzej, Czeslaw.","Polish and Sorbian: metonymic occupational name for someone who grew peas, or a nickname for a physically small person, from Polish and Lower Sorbian <i>groch</i> ‘pea’.","Polish: from a pet form of a personal name such as <i>Grodzisław</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Gruoch mi Boedhe Queen of Scots was born in 1013, in Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Boite mac Cináeda, was 24 and her mother, Lady Boete, was 24. She married Gille Coemgáin mac Máil Brigti Mormaer of Moray about 1032. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1057, in Lumphanan, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 44, and was buried in Iona, Argyll and Bute, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1013–1057":"1013–1057","0970–1033":"0970–1033","1005–1057":"1005–1057","1033–1058":"1033–1058","0990–1033":"0990–1033","0990–Female":"0990–Surnud","1005":"1005","before 1013":"enne 1013","0970":"0970","1058":"1058","1013":"1013","before 1033":"enne 1033","BEF. 1033":"enne 1033","1057":"1057","0990":"0990","1033":"1033","about 1032":"umbes 1032","about 1033":"umbes 1033","Lumphanan, Scotland":"Lumphanan, Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Northumbria, England":"Northumbria, England","Europe":"Europe","Iona, Argyll and Bute, Scotland":"Iona, Argyll and Bute, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Inverness, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness, Inverness-shire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1013–1057":"1013–1057","0970–1033":"0970–1033","1005–1057":"1005–1057","1033–1058":"1033–1058","0990–1033":"0990–1033","0990–Female":"0990–Kuollut","1005":"1005","before 1013":"ennen vuotta 1013","0970":"0970","1058":"1058","1013":"1013","before 1033":"ennen vuotta 1033","BEF. 1033":"ennen vuotta 1033","1057":"1057","0990":"0990","1033":"1033","about 1032":"noin 1032","about 1033":"noin 1033","Lumphanan, Scotland":"Lumphanan, Aberdeenshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Northumbria, England":"Northumbria, England","Europe":"Europe","Iona, Argyll and Bute, Scotland":"Iona, Argyll and Bute, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Perthshire, Sc